<TITLE> UK's Darling gets tough on ministers to cut spending </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ISTANBUL ,Oct 5, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British ministers will have to spell out exactly what spending they think is worth protecting because the Treasury is determined to get borrowing down, finance minister Alistair Darling said on Sunday. In Istanbul for the annual meetings of the International Monetary Fund and World Bank, Darling said every country in the world supported spending billions to get their economies growing and that it was not yet time to withdraw the life-support. But, he added, he was driving home to fellow ministers that at some point borrowing would have to be reined in. "We are being very robust with our colleagues," Darling told reporters. "We have to ensure we take robust measures to bring government borrowing down again. All my colleagues are fully signed up to that." The cost of the worst recession in decades has sent net debt soaring to record levels. Public borrowing this year is expected to top 12.5 percent of gross domestic product, putting pressure on sterling and raising concern about Britain's triple-A credit rating. It has also made public expenditure a central battleground for an election expected next May which Prime Minister Gordon Brown's Labour government looks set to lose to the opposition Conservative Party. So far neither Labour nor the opposition Conservatives have given much detail on how they plan to get borrowing down beyond promises to protect "frontline services". Darling has said he will give further details in the pre-budget report, which is usually held in November, and the government is also expected to enshrine deficit reduction in law then. "All my colleagues are fully signed up to that, they have to say what is important, what the priorities are, what are the frontline services," Darling said. Opposition Conservative leader David Cameron said on Sunday that if elected his government would shake up the welfare system and scrap Labour's flagship "New Deal" jobs programme. "We won't get Britain back to work thro